-- FTSE 100 Benchmark Gains; Xstrata, BHP Billiton Climb, Serco Shares Slump
-- B y   A d a m   H a i g h
-- 2010-11-01T16:50:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-01/betfair-bg-group-bhp-billiton-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
U.K. stocks  gained after a report
showing Chinese manufacturing expanded at the fastest pace in
six months boosted mining shares, outweighing a slump at Serco
Group Plc.  Xstrata Plc and  BHP Billiton Ltd.  followed commodity prices
higher.  Premier Foods Plc  climbed 2.9 percent after Exane BNP
Paribas recommended buying the shares.  Ryanair Holdings Plc  led
Ireland’s ISEQ Index lower even as Europe’s biggest discount
airline raised its earnings forecast.  Serco , which provides
outsourcing services to the U.K. and other governments, sank 4.4
percent as it failed to recoup money from its suppliers.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  rose 19.46, or 0.3 percent, to
5,694.62 at the 4:30 p.m. close in London. The gauge rallied 2.3
percent last month, its second straight monthly gain, amid
speculation the Federal Reserve and other central banks will
step in to boost the ailing economic recovery. The FTSE All-
Share Index also gained 0.3 percent today, while the ISEQ Index
fell 0.3 percent.  “Most of the leading indicators that we follow for
earnings suggest further growth ahead,”  Mislav Matejka , the
head of pan-European equities at JPMorgan Chase & Co. in London,
wrote in a report to clients. “In a nutshell the Fed is siding
itself with the risky assets here, which is very constructive.”  In China, a purchasing managers’ index released by the
logistics federation rose to 54.7 from 53.8 in September, with
input prices climbing the most in six months. A second PMI, from
 HSBC  Holdings Plc and Markit Economics, jumped to 54.8 from
52.9.  Xstrata, BHP Billiton  Xstrata gained 3.7 percent to 1,254.5 pence. BHP Billiton,
the world’s largest mining company, advanced 1 percent to 2,235
pence. Copper, lead, nickel and zinc advanced in London.  Premier Foods  climbed 2.9 percent to 18.11 pence after
Exane  upgraded  the shares to “outperform” from
“underperform.”  Smiths Group Plc, the world’s biggest maker of airport
scanners, rose 3.4 percent to 1,232 pence after British Home
Secretary Theresa May said a device found last week at a U.K.
airport on a cargo aircraft bound for the U.S. “was viable and
could have exploded.”  Ryanair lost 3.8 percent to 3.97 euros as it raised its
profit forecast for 2010.  “Consensus estimates appear to already be at the top end
of the new guidance range,” Arbuthnot Securities Ltd. analyst
 Gerald Khoo  told clients in an e-mail today. He has a “buy”
recommendation on the shares.  Serco Group  sank 4.4 percent to 587 pence after withdrawing
its claims for retrospective cash rebates from its suppliers.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Adam Haigh in London at 
